If you assigned the stream to a local variable you&#39;ll see that type of `Stream.of(1,&quot;Text&quot;)` is `Stream&lt;Object&gt;`

    Stream&lt;Object&gt; x = Stream.of(1,&quot;Text&quot;);

Thus the type of the method that is needed for the forEach is:

    static void method(Object obj){
        System.out.println(&quot;Object is: &quot;+obj);
    }

If you had used `Stream.of(1,2)` or `Stream.of(&quot;Hello&quot;, &quot;Text&quot;)` then the method calls would resolve as you expected.

You can add a method who accept Object parameter, and go with this approach :

    import java.util.stream.Stream;
 
    public class Test {
	static void method(Object o) {
		if(o instanceof String)
			method((String)o);
		if(o instanceof Integer)
			method((Integer)o);
	}
 
	static void method(Integer i) {
		System.out.println(&quot;i&quot;);
	}

	static void method(String i) {
		System.out.println(&quot;s&quot;);
	}

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Stream.of(1, &quot;Text&quot;).forEach(element -&gt; {
 			Test.method( element );
		});
 	}
    }

As the type of elements in `Stream.of(1, &quot;Text&quot;, null)` is the common super type of all three arguments, a method accepting an argument of `Object` type may be implemented to dispatch the call to appropriate overloaded `method` (`null` values should be handled to map to some specific method too):
```java
Stream.of(1,&quot;Text&quot;, null).forEach(Test::method);

static void method(Object o) {
    if (o instanceof Integer) {
        method((Integer) o);
    } else if (o instanceof String || null == o) {
        method((String) o);
    } else {
        method(o.toString());
    }
}
```
Output:
```
i
s
s
```
----
Regarding the statement:
&gt; Not using streams obviously work.

This does not seem to be true.

If a raw list/array is created and used instead of the Stream, a similar issue occurs:
```java
List list = Arrays.asList(1, &quot;Text&quot;, null);
// list.forEach(Test::method); // fails too, same error as below
for (int i = 0; i &lt; list.size(); i++) {
    method(list.get(i));
}
```
In this case error would look like:
```
/Test.java:10: error: no suitable method found for method(Object)
    method(list.get(i));
    ^
    method Test.method(Integer) is not applicable
      (argument mismatch; Object cannot be converted to Integer)
    method Test.method(String) is not applicable
      (argument mismatch; Object cannot be converted to String)
1 error
```

Java only resolves overloads at compile time. You seem to want `Test::method` to resolve to `method(Integer)` (first overload) when iterating over `1`, and resolve to `method(String)` (second overload) when iterating over `&quot;Text&quot;`. That&#39;s not possible, `Test::method` can only resolve to one thing.

The error message is a bit confusing indeed. The problem is not that it is ambiguous between the two methods. The problem is that since you have both strings and integers in the stream, `forEach` expects you to give it a method that can accept _both_ strings and integers (or more accurately, a common supertype between `String` and `Integer`, since there&#39;s no union types in Java).

    static void method(Object o){
    
    }

But neither of the overloads of `method` that you have accepts both strings and integers.

To do what you want, you must check the type at runtime, and call the overload manually:

    Stream.of(1,&quot;Text&quot;).forEach(x -&gt; {
        if (x instanceof Integer) {
            method((Integer)x);
        } else if (x instanceof String) {
            method((String)x);
        }
    });

I would suggest that you _don&#39;t_ put strings and integers together in the same stream.

The situation would be different if the types involved are not `String` and `Integer`, but classes that you wrote. Because then you can write `method` as an instance method in a common superclass. Unlike overload resolution, choosing which overridden implementation of an instance method to run _is_ done at runtime.

```
class Superclass {
  public void method() {
    
  }
}

class BaseClass1 extends Superclass {

  @Override
  public void method() {
    System.out.println(&quot;i&quot;);
  }
}

class BaseClass2 extends Superclass {

  @Override
  public void method() {
    System.out.println(&quot;s&quot;);
  }
}

// ...

Stream.of(new BaseClass1(), new BaseClass2()).forEach(Superclass::method);
```

